04073nam a22005415i 9780889207929DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061998xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892079297 a10.51644/97808892079292doi  a(DE-B1597)667355  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBS480 ǂb H37 1998eb 7aSOC0280002bisacsh04a220.1/31 aHarder, Lydia Neufeld, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aObedience, Suspicion and the Gospel of Mark :bA Mennonite-Feminist Exploration of Biblical Authority /cLydia Neufeld Harder. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in Women and Religion ;v500tFront Matter -- tAcknowledgments -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tMethodological Strategies and Theological Focus -- tDiscipleship and Authority: Mennonite Hermeneutic Community -- tDiscipleship and Authority: Feminist Hermeneutic Community -- tDiscipleship and Authority: The Gospel of Mark -- tAn Invitation to Further Experimentation -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex of Authors and Subjects -- tIndex of Biblical References -- tSeries Published by Wilfrid Laurier University Press for the Canadian Corporation for Studies in Religion / Corporation Canadienne des Sciences Religieuses0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow do our social, political and religious commitments influence our interpretation of biblical texts? Are obedience and suspicion necessarily opposite ways to respond to the authority of the Bible? Can one criticize and be transformed at the same time? Lydia Neufeld Harder explores these questions from the vantage point of a scholar, a feminist and a member of a faith community. A hermeneutics of obedience, rising out of the Mennonite theological tradition, and a hermeneutics of suspicion, advocated by many feminist theologians, seem to represent opposite approaches to the Bible’s authority. The resulting polarization could easily have led to static definitions of authority and the subtle domination of those who differ from the majority. However, by focusing on the common theological concept of discipleship, Harder has constructed a critical dialogue, beginning a process of creative change in her own view of authority. This new view opens the way for an interpretation of the Gospel of Mark. A new appreciation of both the power and the vulnerability of the biblical text leads to a view of authority that embraces both suspicion and obedience in a dynamic interpretative process.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMennonitesxDoctrines. 4aReligion. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920792940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207929423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207929/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles